neutron/agent/dhcp/agent.py.message:
You should not block this. Instead, what you can do is retrieve the flag status, reset the flag, make the call and wait:

def _reload_bulk_allocations(self):
  while True:
    if self._network_bulk_allocations.get(network_id):
      self._network_bulk_allocations[network_id] = False
      network = self.cache.get_network_by_id(network_id)
      self.call_driver('bulk_reload_allocations', network)
    eventlet.greenthread.sleep(self.conf.bulk_reload_interval)

The flag reset should be done at the beginning. If other call is done, the flag will be risen and read in the next loop.

1) Reset flag: be definition, a flag is a boolean parameter. It doesn't matter if you delete it or set to False, whenever you consider None/False the opposite to True.

2) NetworkCache.get_network_by_id: you are right, this can raise an exception. IMO you should modify the method, adding for example raise_exception=False input parameter in the function. If True, then use
  return self.cache.get(network_id, None)

